\begin{lemma}\leanok
[Localizing a module at the powers of \(f\) then at a prime is localizing at the contraction]
  \label{lem:tilde_pullback_stalk_localizationTransitivity}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.tildePullbackComparison_stalk_localizationTransitivity}
  \uses{mathlib:localization_localization_atPrime}
  Let \(R\) be a commutative ring, \(f\in R\), and \(M\) an \(R\)-module.  Let
  \(g:M\to M_f\) exhibit \(M_f\) as the localization of \(M\) at the multiplicative
  submonoid \(\{f^n : n\geq 0\}\) (so \(M_f\) is an \(R_f\)-module via the
  localization \(R\to R_f\)).  Let \(\mathfrak p\subseteq R_f\) be a prime,
  \(\mathfrak q:=\mathfrak p\cap R\) its contraction, and \(h:M_f\to N\) exhibit \(N\)
  as the localization of \(M_f\) at \(\mathfrak p^{c}\) (\(\mathrm{IsLocalizedModule}\,
  \mathfrak p^{c}\), as an \(R_f\)-module hence \(R\)-module).  Then the composite
  \(h\circ g:M\to N\) exhibits \(N\) as the localization of \(M\) at \(\mathfrak q^{c}\):
  \(\mathrm{IsLocalizedModule}\,\mathfrak q^{c}\,(h\circ g)\).
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{mathlib:localization_localization_atPrime}
  \leanok
  This is the transitivity of module localization along the tower
  \(R\to R_f\to(R_f)_{\mathfrak p}\), established directly by verifying the three
  defining clauses of a localized module for the composite \(h\circ g\) at
  \(\mathfrak q^{c}\) (rather than by appealing to a packaged uniqueness statement).
  At ring level, localizing \(R_f=(\{f^n\})^{-1}R\) at \(\mathfrak p\) localizes \(R\)
  at the contracted prime \(\mathfrak q=\mathfrak p\cap R\)
  (\cref{mathlib:localization_localization_atPrime}); concretely
  \(r\in\mathfrak q^{c}\iff\varphi(r)\in\mathfrak p^{c}\) for \(\varphi:R\to R_f\),
  and every power \(f^n\) maps to a unit of \(R_f\), hence lies outside the prime
  \(\mathfrak p\).  With this:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item each \(r\in\mathfrak q^{c}\) acts invertibly on \(N\), because
      \(\varphi(r)\in\mathfrak p^{c}\) acts invertibly through \(h\) and the two
      actions agree by the scalar-tower compatibility;
    \item \(h\circ g\) is surjective onto \(N\): a denominator from \(\mathfrak p^{c}\)
      (cleared by \(h\)) is itself a fraction over \(\{f^n\}\) (cleared by \(g\)), so
      every element of \(N\) is \(\mathfrak q^{c}\)-equivalent to one in the image;
    \item \((h\circ g)(m)=(h\circ g)(m')\) forces \(m,m'\) to agree after multiplying
      by some \(s\in\mathfrak q^{c}\), again by clearing the two layers of denominators.
  \end{itemize}
  Hence \(h\circ g\) exhibits \(N\) as the localization of \(M\) at \(\mathfrak q^{c}\).
\end{proof}

